# React + Vite + Tailwind CSS Development Rules

## Core Principles
- Build scalable and modular React applications using Vite and Tailwind CSS.
- Strictly adhere to responsive design principles for all screen sizes (mobile, tablet, desktop, ultra-wide).
- Ensure zero comments in code. Code should be self-documenting through clear naming conventions.

## Code Constraints
- Maximum file length: 400 lines. If a file exceeds this limit, refactor into smaller, focused modules or components.
- No code comments allowed. Do not include any `//` and `/* */` style comments in any code files.

## Project Structure & Modularity
- Follow a modular project structure (e.g., `src/components`, `src/pages`, `src/hooks`, `src/utils`, `src/assets`).
- Ensure each file strictly serves a single responsibility.
- Extract layout complexities into reusable wrapper components.

## Styling & Responsiveness
- Use Tailwind CSS exclusively for styling.
- All screens, pages, and components MUST be fully responsive and adapt gracefully to all dimensions.
- Explicitly handle responsive sizing using Tailwind's breakpoint prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`, `2xl:`).
- Start with a mobile-first design approach and scale up.

## Component & Logic Guidelines
- Use React functional components.
- Extract complex state management or side-effects into custom hooks.
- Destructure props cleanly.
- Maintain strict type safety or props validation if applicable.
